{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08b66c9f-7873-449d-8cc5-6d8cf8c21057","content":"Use the `--filter` flag with the `&` operator to combine both conditions:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName~Integration & Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n- **`ClassName~Integration`** — `~` means \"contains\", so this matches any test class with \"Integration\" in its name.\n- **`Category=Smoke`** — matches tests decorated with `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]`.\n- **`&`** — logical AND, so both conditions must be true.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9a552477-fb83-4ee1-8288-0e5a4a03b691","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to construct a single combined filter expression for `dotnet test` that:\n\n1. Runs only tests with category \"Smoke\" (or trait \"Category=Smoke\")\n2. Only from classes whose name contains \"Integration\"\n\nIn xUnit v3 with `dotnet test`, you use the `--filter` flag with a single expression. The filter syntax supports:\n\n- `FullyQualifiedName` — matches the full test name\n- `DisplayName` — matches the display name\n- `Category` — matches the `[Trait(\"Category\", \"...\")]` value (xUnit v3 maps this)\n\n\n- `ClassName` — matches the class name\n\nYou can combine conditions with `&` (AND), `|` (OR), and `~` (contains). So the combined filter would be a command that uses both the class name pattern and the category trait together to narrow down which tests run.","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"1BCC:1BD824:CC5F72:E7633B:6A03D64B"},"id":"28a98481-066d-4a44-968a-b856a868bb6a","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:39:30.985Z","parentId":"d97b2806-82f9-4a16-8882-55d38dcd51bb"}
